{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/hero-youll-never-have-to-watch-long-videos-again-ee0d5e2ba4fd", "time": 1683014038.382226, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/hero-youll-never-have-to-watch-long-videos-again-ee0d5e2ba4fd/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "HERO: You\u2019ll never have to watch long videos again | by Rohit Pillai | Towards Data Science", "h1": "HERO: You\u2019ll never have to watch long videos again", "description": "Have you ever had to watch 15 lectures worth of material the night before an exam? Or submit a report about a 2-hour movie that you haven\u2019t watched in the next hour? I know I have. Luckily, my\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/uniter-d979e2d838f0", "anchor_text": "UNITER", "paragraph_index": 2}, {"url": "https://medium.com/swlh/violin-do-you-really-understand-videos-fe07f7affd9e", "anchor_text": "Video-Language Inference", "paragraph_index": 11}, {"url": "https://tvr.cs.unc.edu/index.html", "anchor_text": "TVR", "paragraph_index": 11}, {"url": "https://tvr.cs.unc.edu/tvc.html", "anchor_text": "TVC", "paragraph_index": 11}, {"url": "https://arxiv.org/pdf/2005.00200.pdf", "anchor_text": "link", "paragraph_index": 13}, {"url": "https://github.com/linjieli222/HERO", "anchor_text": "link", "paragraph_index": 13}, {"url": "https://aka.ms/mmai", "anchor_text": "here", "paragraph_index": 13}, {"url": "https://medium.com/@rohit.rameshp", "anchor_text": "https://medium.com/@rohit.rameshp", "paragraph_index": 15}], "all_paragraphs": ["Have you ever had to watch 15 lectures worth of material the night before an exam? Or submit a report about a 2-hour movie that you haven\u2019t watched in the next hour? I know I have. Luckily, my lecture videos were marked with where content started and ended so I could just skim through them. But what if those markers weren\u2019t there? Fear not: HERO is here to save you!", "\u201cWhat is HERO and how will it save me?\u201d, you might ask. Your question will be answered but first, let me give you some context. If you\u2019ve read some of my previous posts, you\u2019ll probably know that machine learning is moving towards the direction of large scale pretrained models, which are models that are given a lot of data initially and learn from them. These models can then apply this knowledge to a specific task to achieve better performances than most others.", "Pretrained models like BERT, RoBERTa and ALBERT have taken over the field of NLP and the multimodal field is starting to develop them too. Models like UNITER and Unicoder-VL have been big strides in the image+text pretraining space.", "However, one space that hasn\u2019t been explored all that much is the video+text space. Ideally, this should be a very natural extension. After all, videos are just a sequence of images. There have been a few attempts to tackle this space through models like CBT and UniViLM, but they fail to capture a key aspect of videos: their order. Instead they treat videos and their subtitles as a bunch of images and text without considering that a subtitle is only relevant for certain frames and that the order of the frames matter.", "In order to remedy this, the researchers at Microsoft Dynamics 365 AI Research propose Hierarchical EncodeR for Omnirepresentation learning (HERO). Unlike previous models for video+text, HERO accounts for the sequence of the video and how the text maps to it.", "To do this, HERO uses a 2-layer hierarchical structure. The first layer uses a \u201ccross-modal\u201d transformer which fuses text and image. It matches each sentence from the subtitles to the corresponding part of video. The output of this \u201ccross-modal\u201d transformer is then used by a \u201ctemporal\u201d transformer to learn the order of the different frames of the video. This hierarchical learning is made possible through 4 main pre-training tasks.", "In MLM, HERO is given a subtitle sentence with some missing words and the corresponding video frames and HERO is expected to generate those missing words.", "MFM is like MLM for images except that it is done with the whole video as context. The input is all the subtitle sentences and most of the video frames. HERO\u2019s job is to generate the missing frames.", "VSM is what it sounds like for the most part. HERO is given one sentence from the subtitles as a query and the context is the all the subtitle sentences and all the video frames. HERO has to learn a local alignment i.e. identify the frames of the video that the query sentence corresponds to.", "But there\u2019s a catch. The provided video may not even match the subtitles. This helps HERO learn what a sentence should look like and vice versa.", "While MLM, MFM and FOM are all used to train the \u201ccross-modal\u201d transformer, FOM is used to train the \u201ctemporal\u201d transformer. It takes the output of the 3 previous tasks and a jumbled set of frames to predict the correct order of frames.", "After the pre-training tasks worked their magic and HERO was trained, the researchers tested its power on several different tasks including Video Captioning, Video Question Answering, Video-Moment Retrieval (retrieving a specific part of the video based on a sentence) and Video-Language Inference. HERO was able to beat the best models on all these tasks and even achieved the #1 position on the TVR (TV-Retrieval) and TVC (TV-Captioning) leaderboards.", "So don\u2019t wait, let HERO save you from those last minute lecture/documentary/movie watches!", "Here\u2019s a link to the paper if you want to know more about the HERO model, a link to the code for you to train your own and click here to see more of our publications and other work.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "I\u2019m an engineer at Microsoft Dynamics 365 AI Research and I\u2019ll post our new NLP, CV and Multimodal research . Check out https://medium.com/@rohit.rameshp"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"u